    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1932-02-26T00:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1932-02-26T00:00:00-05:00" n="482"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d482">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/4429: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in China (<persName corresp="#p_JNT1" type="from"
                            >Johnson</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Shanghai</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-02-26T13:00:00+08:00"
                            >February 26, 1932—1 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received February 26—10:10 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>From Captain <persName corresp="#p_MCW1">Mayer</persName> for the War Department:
                        <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>12. Japanese 11th Division will probably debark today, point of
                            debarkation undetermined. With the arrival of reenforcements Japanese
                            right wing will be strengthened and extended and Woosung Chinese
                            garrison undoubtedly isolated. Chinese have withstood most intense air
                            and some artillery bombardment at Kiangwan and northwest throughout
                            yesterday. At February 26, 10 a.m., Chinese still in Kiangwan and
                            February 25, 6 p.m., Japanese casualties for day 130. Chinese dogged
                            resistance in the face of powerful air attacks most astounding.</p>
                        <p>
                            <persName corresp="#p_MY1">Matsuoka</persName> told <persName
                                corresp="#p_WKHV1">Von Wiegand</persName> today that Japanese will
                            not push beyond 20-kilometer zone. General <persName corresp="#p_W1"
                                >Wetzel</persName> in Shanghai said all German advisers had been
                            given leave by Chinese Government during hostilities. That defense
                            arrangement is result of 4 years’ German <pb facs="0552" n="448"
                                xml:id="pg_448"/> instruction in post-war tactics for use against an
                            enemy greatly superior in mechanical auxiliaries.</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_JNT1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
